# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The **1936 Summer Olympics torch relay** was the first of its kind, following on from the reintroduction of the Olympic Flame at the 1928 Games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] It pioneered the modern convention of moving the flame via a relay system from Greece to the Olympic venue.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Leni Riefenstahl filmed the relay for the award-winning but controversial 1938 film *Olympia*.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The Olympic flame was introduced to the modern Games in 1928 when it burnt atop a pillar above the stadium in Amsterdam.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Four years later the same was repeated in Los Angeles.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] At both of these events the flame was lit on site at the stadium.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Carl Diem used the idea of the torch relay devised for the 1936 Summer Olympics in Berlin by a Jewish archaeologist and sports official, Alfred Schiff.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] According to the official report for the Games, the torch relay was conceived as a publicity stunt to increase awareness for the Games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The process was ratified by the International Olympic Committee and has been repeated at all the Games that have followed.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Diem and the organizing team realized that there would need to be very detailed plans in order to successfully complete the relay to a standard that would satisfy both themselves and the ruling Third Reich.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] At the time they were unsure about exactly how they could use the sun's rays to start the fire as well as how to create a torch that would remain alight whatever the conditions.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Research was therefore required into the specialist technologies that would be needed.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The route itself would need development and the path down from Olympia was deemed too difficult to access.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The organising committees therefore agreed that new roads would be built to ensure that the relay got off to the best possible start.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Adolf Hitler saw the link with the ancient Games as the perfect way to illustrate his belief that classical Greece was an Aryan forerunner of the modern German Reich.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The event was designed to demonstrate the growing influence and power of the Third Reich.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] It was internationally viewed as a great success, sufficient for it to be replicated in all Games thereafter.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Leni Riefenstahl, a film-maker admired by Hitler, filmed the relay for the 1938 release *Olympia*.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] While the film is often seen as a prime example of Nazi propaganda, it has also been hailed as one of the greatest films of all time and won many awards upon its release.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Sculptor Walter Lemcke designed the 27 cm wood and metal torches.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] German manufacturer Krupp produced 3,840 copies for the runners, over 500 more than would be needed.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] It was designed with two fuses to help it cope with different weather conditions and could stay alight for ten minutes, longer than each section of the route.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] On 20 July 1936 the Olympic flame was lit in Greece by a concave mirror made by German company Zeiss.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The Nazi Party wanted to demonstrate their organisational prowess and enhance their influence on various countries along the route of the relay.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The torch travelled through south-eastern and central European countries to demonstrate and enhance their influence.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The National Olympic Committees (NOCs) of the countries along the route all agreed to support the relay which would pass through Greece, Bulgaria, Yugoslavia, Hungary, Austria, and Czechoslovakia and then Germany.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] These countries would fall under Nazi domination as the second World War began just over three years later.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] In Austria, a country that would be annexed into the Third Reich less than two years after the relay, the torch was met by major pro-Nazi public demonstrations.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] In all the torch was transported over 3,187 kilometres by 3,331 runners in twelve days and eleven nights from Greece to Berlin.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Much of the route was split into kilometre-long sections and it was anticipated that each runner would traverse that distance in five minutes, though some leeway was given to allow for difficult terrain and sparsely populated areas.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The names of most of the torch bearers, all of whom were male, were not recorded.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Two urns in the centre of Berlin, within two long rows of large swastika flags, were lit by 400m-runner Siegfried Eifrig on 1 August 1936.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The urns burnt for the duration of the Games and served as the starting point for the final relay runner.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Fritz Schilgen, a three time 1500m champion, was suggested by former German athletics president Karl Ritter von Halt as the final runner.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Schilgen, viewed as a "symbol of German sporting youth", was accepted by the three advisory boards.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1936-summer-olympics-torch-relay] One of these, the aesthetics commission, included film-maker Riefenstahl on the panel.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1940-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Though the whole event was eventually cancelled due to the outbreak of war, the **1940 Summer Olympics torch relay** was planned for both of the proposed host cities.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1940-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The International Olympic Committee (IOC) awarded the 1940 Summer Olympics to Tokyo, Japan in July 1936.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1940-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Tokyo's ability to host the event was questioned after war broke out with China (the Second Sino-Japanese War) with some countries calling for the Games to be boycotted.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1940-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The Japanese decided to cancel the event and Helsinki, Finland, the runner-up city in the bidding process, was selected as the replacement.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1940-summer-olympics-torch-relay] That too was cancelled after the outbreak of World War II.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1940-summer-olympics-torch-relay] At the 1936 Summer Olympics in Berlin the first torch relay event took place, starting a tradition that has continued in all the Games that have taken place since.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1940-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Both National Olympic Committees had given details about their plan for the Olympic Torch relay.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1940-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The distance from Olympia to Berlin made it possible to hold a relay on foot in a reasonable amount of time, but the distance to Tokyo gave the IOC cause for concern.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1940-summer-olympics-torch-relay] They discussed the viability of such an undertaking on numerous occasions and eventually decided that they should try to replicate the success of the inaugural torch relay using "[s]teamers, automobiles, and airplanes".
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1940-summer-olympics-torch-relay] A report into the progress made on the planning of the Games stated that there would be a significant benefit "in diffusing the Olympic spirit in the districts where the knowledge of the Olympic movement is as yet very scanty".
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1940-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The organisation team behind the 1936 relay made recommendations to the Japanese Olympic Committee about how it could be completed.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1940-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Their suggestions would see the torch carried for 10,000 km by runners and horse riders, travelling along the Silk Road across Central Asia.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1940-summer-olympics-torch-relay] A significant portion of the relay would therefore take place across China, an idea not favoured by the Japanese.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1940-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Another proposal, coming from Germany, was to pioneer the idea of air delivery of the Torch, in the purpose-built Messerschmitt Me 261 *Adolfine* long-range aircraft, which was designed to have a maximum range of some 11,024 km (6,850 mi) unrefueled.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1940-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Several suggestions were made by the Japanese Olympic Committee about how the flame could be taken from Olympia to Tokyo.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1940-summer-olympics-torch-relay] One proposal was for the torch to be carried on board a Japanese warship, but a later idea was for it to be taken by the *Kamikaze*, a Mitsubishi Ki-15 plane, across southern Asia.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1940-summer-olympics-torch-relay] When the flame arrived in Japan it would be carried from Mount Hyūga in Kyushu to Tokyo via the Ise Shrine.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1940-summer-olympics-torch-relay] A relay from Olympia to Tokyo eventually took place when the city hosted the 1964 Summer Olympics.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1940-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The Finnish Olympic Committee planned an ambitious relay that would cross Europe.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1940-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The first part of the route would be very similar to that of 1936 as the torch travelled up to Berlin, the only addition being a detour to Slovakia.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1940-summer-olympics-torch-relay] From there it would make its way through to Scandinavia, taken by a rowing boat where necessary.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1940-summer-olympics-torch-relay] There was a further proposal that the flame would make its way to every Olympic Stadium in each host city of the previous ten Summer Games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1940-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Cauldrons at these locations would also keep the flame burning for the duration of the Games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1940-summer-olympics-torch-relay] While the torch route would include Athens, Berlin, and Stockholm the other host cities were further afield and would require alternative arrangements.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1940-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Suggestions included branching off the relay to the European cities but it would be more difficult to arrange travel to the two in the United States.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The **1948 Summer Olympics torch relay** was run from 17 July until 29 July 1948, prior to the 1948 Summer Olympics, held in London, United Kingdom.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The relay was nicknamed the "relay of peace".
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] It was only the second occasion that a torch relay was held for the Olympics; the first was at the 1936 Summer Olympics.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] There were three types of torches designed for use on the relay: a standard solid fuel powered torch made of aluminium, a special butane gas torch used on board HMS *Whitesand Bay*, and a final torch used to enter Empire Stadium that was made of stainless steel and powered by a magnesium candle.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The route itself was initially designed to be a direct one from Olympia to Wembley, taking in Italy, Switzerland and France.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Belgium and Luxembourg were added to the route after those countries requested it.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] It was expected that the Greek part of the relay would be 750 kilometres (470 mi), but was reduced to 35 kilometres (22 mi) due to concerns over security.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] After the 12-day journey, the torch arrived at the Empire Stadium only thirty seconds later than expected.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] London having hosted the 1908 Summer Olympics, the 1948 event was only the second Games to stage an Olympic torch relay, it being first run at the 1936 Summer Olympics in Berlin.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Former British athlete David Cecil, 6th Marquess of Exeter, and the rest of the organising committee for the 1948 Games, agreed to run a torch relay for a second time.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Each of the torches contained a solid fuel tablet made of hexamine and 6% naphthalene (following torch running tests in May 1947) that fuelled the flame itself.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The solid fuel increased the distance each runner could run to 2 miles (3.2 km) over flat terrain, decreasing the number of torches needed to be produced, which in turn reduced the cost of the relay.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] There were eight tablets loaded into each torch, with the bottom tablets pushed up by the use of a spring.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The design increased the burning time of each torch up to around fifteen minutes, an increase from the four-minute torches of the 1936 Olympics.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The torch itself was designed by Ralph Lavers, with the brief that it should be "inexpensive and easy to make, of pleasing appearance and a good example of British craftmanship".
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The torches were made from aluminium, with a long shaft holding a cup that contained the burner.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] "With thanks to the bearer" was written on the cup of the torch itself, along with the Olympic rings.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The torches for the Greek leg of the relay were shipped to the Mediterranean aboard HMS *Liverpool*, along with a purpose-built torch for the leg aboard a Royal Navy vessel from Corfu to Italy.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] A differently designed torch was used for the final leg.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] It was made of stainless steel and was fueled by magnesium in order to ensure that the flame showed up properly during the opening ceremony.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] It was also designed by Ralph Lavers, with the frame for the torch created by EMI, and the magnesium candle supplied by Wessex Aircraft Engineering.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Neither the suppliers nor designer charged a fee for the final torch.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] While the general negotiation with other countries and the specific route were handled by the Organising Committee for the Games, the detailed organisation was delegated to a subgroup led by F.W.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Due to cost implications, the extensive route conducted by the 1936 Games was ruled out.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Instead, the simplest route from Olympia to London was to be used, going by sea to Italy and then run through Switzerland and France.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The route was modified only when Luxembourg and Belgium both requested that the torch travel their territories.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] A longer Greek route was planned, but reduced from an expected 750 kilometres (470 mi) down to 35 kilometres (22 mi) due to concerns over the civil war in the country and a lack of security.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The torch lighting ceremony took place on 17 July 1948 in Olympia, Greece.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] As with the 1936 Summer Olympic relay, the torch relay was begun by focusing the sun's rays onto kindling using a parabolic reflector, which then lit the first torch.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The kindling was conducted by a Girl Guide leader from Pyrgos, Elis.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] She was only chosen the previous evening due to the unsettled state of the country; the Athenian girl who was trained for the ceremony was unable to travel to Olympia.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] In a symbolic gesture, the first runner, Corporal Dimitrelis of the Greek Army, laid down his arms and removed his military uniform before taking his torch in hand.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The kindling material for the first torch was handed over as a gift from the Chairman of the Greek Olympic Committee to Collins, for Princess Elizabeth.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] It was then run to the Greek coast at Katakolo, where at 7 pm it boarded the Greek destroyer *Hastings* bound for the island of Corfu.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The ship dropped the torch off in Bari at 12:30 pm on 19 July.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] It was run north through several Italian cities before crossing the Simplon Pass into Brig, Switzerland on 23 July.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] From there it was run west until leaving the country at Perly-Certoux, and entering France at Saint-Julien-en-Genevois.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The route then detours from the direct route to take in Luxembourg and into Belgium before re-entering France at Lille on 28 July, finally departing the country at Calais.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] HMS *Bicester* carried the torch across the English Channel to Dover, arriving at 8:25 pm on 28 July.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] It travelled through several towns in the South East of England until it arrived at Wembley, where it arrived only thirty seconds late after the entire journey.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] That delay may have only been in the final few hundred yards of the relay down Olympic Way outside of Empire Stadium as the pressure of the crowds on the torch carrier and their escorts reduced the pace to walking speed.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Special celebrations were held at each border crossing, and at Pierre de Coubertin's tomb in Lausanne, Switzerland.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] It was agreed for a secondary Olympic Flame to be lit in Torquay during the games (as the town hosted the sailing events), and a secondary torch relay was conducted to take the flame from Wembley south to the coast to Torquay.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1948-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The arrangements were the same as from Dover to Wembley but in reverse.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The **1952 Summer Olympics torch relay** was the symbolic transport of the Olympic flame from Olympia, Greece, to the venue of the 1952 Summer Olympics in Helsinki, Finland, where it featured as part of the opening ceremony.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The 1952 Olympic flame was lit at a ceremony using the sun's rays in Olympia, from where it started its journey on 25 June.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-summer-olympics-torch-relay] On 6 July, a second flame was lit on top of the Taivaskero peak of Pallastunturi fell in the Finnish Lapland.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The intention had been to ignite it with the rays of the midnight sun, but due to overcast conditions that night some additional 'tricks' were required.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-summer-olympics-torch-relay] This 'Midnight Sun Torch' was carried 378 kilometres (235 mi) south to the city of Tornio near the Swedish border, where it met the one from Olympia, the latter having meanwhile been carried north the length of Sweden.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The two flames were merged for the remainder of their journey.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The torches were made of either solid silver or silver-plated brass, with a lacquered curly birch handle.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The fuel was liquid gas contained in a cartridge which was quick and easy to replace.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-summer-olympics-torch-relay] For this reason, only 22 torches were needed, as well as 1,600 fuel cartridges.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Because of the small number produced, the 1952 torch is a rarity not found in many collections, and therefore highly collectable: at a 2011 auction in Paris, one was sold for the record price of €290,000 or nearly US$400,000.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The torch was designed by Finnish graphic designer and visual artist Aukusti Tuhka and manufactured by the precious metals company Kultakeskus.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The flame was carried from Olympia to Athens, from where it was flown to Aalborg, Denmark, via two intermediary stops in West Germany (in Munich and Düsseldorf).
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-summer-olympics-torch-relay] There were celebrations held at each stop of the journey.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-summer-olympics-torch-relay] This was the first time the Olympic flame was flown out of Greece.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Next, the flame traversed Denmark over land and water by different modes of transport, finishing with crossing the Øresund strait from Copenhagen to Malmö, Sweden.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-summer-olympics-torch-relay] In Sweden the flame was carried overland via Gothenburg to Stockholm, where on 4 July it was kept burning overnight at the 1912 Olympics stadium.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Afterwards it continued its journey north, eventually leaving Sweden by crossing the northern land border to Finland, where it was united with the 'Midnight Torch' flame on 8 July.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Over the next ten days the torch was carried south by 1,350 runners, arriving in Helsinki on the opening day of the games, 19 July.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-summer-olympics-torch-relay] On its final stage through the city of Helsinki, the relay procession was fronted by a police car in radio contact with the organisers at the stadium, with the intention of adjusting the relay pace as needed.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Consequently, the torch arrived at the stadium with perfect timing.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The total relay distance was 7,492 kilometres (4,655 mi), excluding the separate 'Midnight Sun Torch' relay from Pallastunturi to Tornio.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The route took in the cities of, among others, Aalborg, Aarhus, Copenhagen, Malmö, Gothenburg, Stockholm, Uppsala, Tornio, Oulu, Jyväskylä, Tampere and Hämeenlinna, before reaching Helsinki.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-summer-olympics-torch-relay] A commemorative copper medal was given to each person carrying the torch on its journey.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The flame was brought to the Helsinki Olympic Stadium by the Finnish long-distance runner Paavo Nurmi, himself a winner of multiple gold and silver medals at the 1920, 1924 and 1928 Olympics.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-summer-olympics-torch-relay] He used the torch to light a temporary cauldron on the stadium field.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The actual cauldron was situated on top of the stadium tower, 72 metres (236 ft) above the ground.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Four players from a Helsinki football club ran up the tower with the torch, passing it to another Finnish long-distance runner, Hannes Kolehmainen, also a winner of multiple medals at the 1912 and 1920 Olympics, who finally lit the main cauldron.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-winter-olympics-torch-relay] The **1952 Winter Olympics torch relay** was the first time that a flame was transported as part of the build-up to the Winter Olympics.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-winter-olympics-torch-relay] While similar to the inaugural Summer Olympics torch relay of 1936 the Olympic Flame did not start in Olympia, instead the relay began in Morgedal, Norway, the birthplace of competitive skiing.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-winter-olympics-torch-relay] Indeed, the Norwegian Olympic Committee were keen to stress that this was not the traditional transfer of the Olympic flame but a separate event that symbolised the use of torches while skiing in the dark.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-winter-olympics-torch-relay] It was not until the 1964 Winter Olympics that the relay could be said to transport a true Olympic flame originating from Olympia.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-winter-olympics-torch-relay] Bjaaland, a teacher in Morgedal, proposed the idea of a cross-country ski relay from Morgedal to Oslo in 1948.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-winter-olympics-torch-relay] The process was seen as a good way to mark the commencement of the Games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-winter-olympics-torch-relay] The International Olympic Committee (IOC) agreed that the relay could go ahead, including winning support from the IOC president, but that this relay would not carry the true Olympic flame as had been established as protocol in the Summer Games since 1936.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-winter-olympics-torch-relay] Instead this torch was passed in the same way that Norwegian skiers historically did while travelling in the dark.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-winter-olympics-torch-relay] Organisational duties were given to the committee for decorations and ceremonies.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-winter-olympics-torch-relay] The flame would not be lit in Olympia, and a location would be chosen that symbolised the birthplace of skiing and Winter events.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-winter-olympics-torch-relay] Since the 1964 relay the process has changed to bring the relay in line with the Summer Olympics and to officially carry the Olympic flame.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-winter-olympics-torch-relay] While there were attempts to give the "Morgedal Flame" the same significance as the Olympic flame the IOC have insisted that all Olympic Games should use the symbolic fire lit in Olympia.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-winter-olympics-torch-relay] The nine inch long torch was designed to cope with any weather condition that the relay team would face.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-winter-olympics-torch-relay] Its cylindrical handle was topped off by a large, oval collar that depicted the Olympic rings, the year, and an arrow pointing from the start and end points of the relay (Morgedal and Oslo).
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-winter-olympics-torch-relay] A total of 94 renowned skiers or their descendants participated in the relay, the names of whom remained secret until they began their leg of the journey.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-winter-olympics-torch-relay] The relay began on 13 February at the Morgedal home of Sondre Norheim, a pioneer in competitive skiing.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-winter-olympics-torch-relay] The location was chosen to celebrate the birthplace of skiing and the origins of such sporting events.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-winter-olympics-torch-relay] In 1868 Norheim had skied from Morgedal to Oslo to compete in a skiing competition that was being hosted in the city.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-winter-olympics-torch-relay] It would be fitting for a person of high regard to start the relay.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-winter-olympics-torch-relay] Olav Bjaaland, the grandfather of the man who proposed the relay, was a member of the 1911 South Pole expedition.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-winter-olympics-torch-relay] He was given the honour of kindling the fire, and did so by lighting a pine torch in the hearth of Norheim's home.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-winter-olympics-torch-relay] He then passed the flame to the first relay skier.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-winter-olympics-torch-relay] The torch relay then followed the route that Norheim is believed to have taken to Oslo.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-winter-olympics-torch-relay] The final stretch of the relay to Bislett was undertaken by ski champion Lauritz Bergendahl on 15 February.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-winter-olympics-torch-relay] On arrival at the Marathon Gate of the Stadium he passed the torch to the final torch-bearer, Eigil Nansen, grandson of explorer, winter event champion and Nobel Peace Prize-winning diplomat Fridtjof Nansen.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1952-winter-olympics-torch-relay] Nansen skied with the torch around the snow embankment before walking up to and lighting the "Olympic Altar".
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] The **1960 Winter Olympics torch relay** was held in the leadup to the 1960 Winter Olympics in Squaw Valley (now Olympic Valley), California, in the United States, from January 31 to February 18, 1960.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] It was the first torch relay in the Americas, although a flame had previously been lit at the 1932 Summer Olympics in Los Angeles.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] For the final time, the Olympic flame was not lit in the Greek city of Olympia.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] The relay instead began in Morgedal, Norway, as had been done for the first Winter Olympics torch relay in 1952.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] The responsibility for organizing the torch relay, in addition to the opening and closing ceremonies, fell to the Pageantry Committee and its chairman Walt Disney.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] Disney brought many employees of his company WED Enterprises (now known as Walt Disney Imagineering), who had recently designed and begun operating Disneyland, to organize these events.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] The committee intended for the flame to be lit in Olympia, Greece, which was the established tradition for Summer Olympics but had never been done before in the Winter Olympics.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] However, the Hellenic Olympic Committee, which is responsible for lighting the flame at Olympia and transporting it through Greece before it is handed off to the organizing committee of the current Olympics, was only informed of these plans a few days before the relay was set to begin.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] The Games' organizers quickly turned to the Norwegian Olympic Committee, asking them to light the flame at Morgedal, the birthplace of competitive skiing, as had been done for the 1952 relay.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] Norwegian officials agreed, and the flame was lit at Morgedal on January 31, where it was carried to Sondre Norheim's chalet by skier Olav Nordskog.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] It was then transported by car through Oslo to Copenhagen, Denmark, from which it was flown to Los Angeles.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] The torch was designed by Disney artist John Hench, who modeled it after the torches used in 1948 and 1956.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] The International Olympic Committee credits Ralph Lavers, who created the 1948 torch, as co-designing the 1960 torch with Hench.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] However, Hench found these torches to be too top-heavy and difficult to carry, and produced a smaller model which has influenced the design of later Olympic torches.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] The torch bears the inscriptions "VIII Olympic Winter Games 1960" and "Olympia to Squaw Valley", reflecting the canceled plan to light the flame in Greece.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] The Olympic flame arrived at Los Angeles International Airport on the morning of February 1, 1960.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] A Scandinavian Airlines jet liner carried it over the North Pole on its way to the United States.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] From the airport, a helicopter carried the torch to Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum, where the opening and closing ceremonies of the 1932 Summer Olympics had been held.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] Shot put champion Parry O'Brien was the first American to carry the torch, handing it to Los Angeles mayor Norris Poulson.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] The first segment of the relay was run entirely on foot from Los Angeles to Stockton, with runners carrying the flame for roughly six hours per day and typically stopping in the mid-afternoon.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] For most of its journey across California, the torch was carried by high school athletes from all around the state.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] The California Interscholastic Federation organized the selection of torchbearers, with high school coaches allowed to choose one student each.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] Approximately 600 students participated in the relay, each one carrying the flame for one mile.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] Renault, a sponsor of the 1960 Winter Olympics, provided pace cars which followed the relay, picked up and dropped off runners, and supplied them with torches and fuel.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] The cars were driven by officers of the California Highway Patrol.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] On the first day of the relay, the torch was carried from Los Angeles to Glendale and into the San Fernando Valley before stopping for the night in Burbank.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] Gymnasts from Burbank's John Burroughs High School, including a young Dan Haggerty, formed a human pyramid that lifted the torch up and used it to light a large replica torch in front of City Hall.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] Similar lighting ceremonies were staged in many of the towns the relay passed through, and these torches continued burning until the Olympics ended.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] On February 2, the runners passed through San Fernando, Newhall, and Castaic (the latter two now part of Santa Clarita), then following the Ridge Route before stopping for the night in Gorman.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] Entering the San Joaquin Valley, the arrival of the flame coincided with the opening of the first segment of eight-lane freeway that would become Interstate 5 in Grapevine, and the torchbearers and pace cars were the first to use the new roadway.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] The relay's third day ended in Bakersfield.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] On February 4, the runners passed through Delano, where a flock of doves was released.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] In Earlimart, runners followed the recessed freeway through town, but after an outcry from local residents who had expected the torch to stop, they were given an offshoot of the flame.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] From Tipton, another offshoot flame was carried eastward to Porterville while the primary flame continued north.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] The relay stopped for the evening in Tulare, with Olympians Bob Mathias and Sim Iness (both of whom grew up in Tulare) carrying the torch into town.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] The next day, the relay stopped briefly in Kingsburg and Selma, where the lighting of the torch coincided with the unveiling of a memorial to local resident Ancel Robinson, who had broken the world record in the low hurdles in 1957.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] Runners officially ended the day on the steps of the Memorial Auditorium in Fresno, where the torch was greeted by Olympic athlete and former Fresno mayor Gordon Dunn and Olympic figure skater Carole Ormaca.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] Another offshoot flame was carried from Fresno to Sanger.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] The relay's sixth day had the torch stop in Madera and end its run in Merced.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] On February 7, the run passed through Atwater, Livingston, and Delhi before a midday stop in Turlock, then proceeded through Ceres before finishing the day in Modesto.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] The final day of the first running segment took the torch to Ripon before it arrived in Stockton at noon on February 8.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] From Stockton, the torch boarded the motor yacht *Adventuress*, part of the ceremonial "Great Golden Fleet", and sailed down the San Joaquin River to the Ferry Building in San Francisco.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] It was then run through the city before ending the day at City Hall.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] The next day, the *Adventuress* carried the torch back across the San Francisco Bay for a ceremony at Jack London Square in Oakland, before returning it to Stockton in the evening.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] The foot relay resumed on February 10, with runners carrying the torch north from Stockton, through Thornton, and into Sacramento, where Governor Pat Brown lit a cauldron on the steps of the California State Capitol.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] The next day, it was run through Roseville and Auburn.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] While Auburn was the planned stopping point for February 11, runners continued that day to carry the torch all the way to Colfax, before it was driven back to Auburn to spend the night.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] On February 12, Lincoln's Birthday, the torch was driven to Colfax for the final running leg to Emigrant Gap.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] From Emigrant Gap, the torch was carried through the Sierra Nevada mountains by cross-country skiers, who brought it to the summit of Little Papoose Peak, just above the resort complex which had been built for the Games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] While preparing for the final leg of the relay, organizers found that their torches could not withstand the anticipated high winds and would be blown out.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] As a result, instead of the standard torch design, a souvenir torch capable of holding a road flare was used.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] Olympic Committee member in Tulare, who had to give it back the day before the opening ceremonies.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] Upon reaching the summit of Little Papoose Peak on the afternoon of February 18, the torch was brought down the ski jump ramp by Andrea Mead Lawrence, accompanied by an honor guard of eight members of the National Ski Patrol.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] Lawrence entered Blyth Arena, the opening ceremony venue, and passed the flame on to speed skater Ken Henry.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1960-winter-olympics-torch-relay] Henry circled the ice rink, then lit the cauldron to mark the beginning of the Games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The **1968 Summer Olympics torch relay** took part as part of the build-up to the 1968 Summer Olympics hosted in Mexico City, Mexico.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The Olympic flame was lit in Olympia, Greece, and retraced the steps of Christopher Columbus, discoverer of the New World.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] This theme celebrated the link between Latin-American and Mediterranean civilizations.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] At the end of the relay the Olympic cauldron was for the first time lit by a female athlete.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Mexican hurdler Enriqueta Basilio was chosen to complete the final leg of the 2,500 kilometres (1,600 mi) running relay.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The torch had covered a total distance of 13,620 kilometres (8,460 mi) including the crossing of the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] While the relay was largely successful it was marred by problems when exchanging the flame from one torch to another.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Runners in Barcelona and Medinaceli were burned by small explosions as a lit torch came into contact with an unlit one.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] American sculptor James Metcalf, an expatriate, won the commission to forge the torch for the Games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] There were two torch designs used throughout the relay: Type A and Type B.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The Type B torch was designed to follow the theme of the logo.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] It is grooved along its length and features a three-dimensional "MEXICO 68" at the top.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] It is kept at a Spanish private club, Real Sociedad de Tenis de la Magdalena in Santander, Spain.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The torch used as a fuel source a compressed mix of nitrates, sulphur, alkaline metal carbonates, resins and silicones.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Problems with the torch occurred in Barcelona and then again in Medinaceli which saw minor explosions burn some torch-bearers.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The cause was investigated and then attributed to "the too-rapid contact of a lighted torch with an unlighted one".
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Precautions were put in place to prevent further incidents.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] For the first time runners from different nations took part in the relay.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] In each previous torch relay the National Olympic Committee (NOC) for the host nation provided all the torch-bearers, but for this event each country through which the torch passed was allowed to select their own representatives.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The route was designed to replicate that taken by Christopher Columbus in his first visit to the New World.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The flame was lit in Olympia and then taken to Athens where a ceremony greeted it on 24 August 1968.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] From there runners carried the torch to the port of Piraeus and it was taken aboard the Greek destroyer HNS *Navarino*.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The vessel sailed to Genoa, arriving there on 27 August where, outside the birthplace of Christopher Columbus, a special tribute was held.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The following day saw the flame begin its journey to Barcelona aboard the *Palinuro*, an Italian Navy training vessel.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The relay crossed several Spanish provinces on its way to Palos de la Frontera, finally being carried into the port by Cristóbal Colón Carbajal, a direct descendant of Columbus.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The crossing of the Atlantic Ocean began on 12 September and was overseen by the Spanish government who provided the *Princesa* for the journey.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] On 29 September 1968 the Flame arrived just outside San Salvador at the original landing site of Columbus's first voyage.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] A celebration organised in conjunction with the Bahamas Olympic Association marked the first time that the Flame had been to the New World.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] At the end of the festivities the Flame was taken aboard the Mexican destroyer ARM *Durango*.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The ship arrived in Veracruz on 6 October with the torch being swam ashore by a relay of seventeen swimmers.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] From there the Mexican runners started their journey, and the Flame arrived at the Estadio Olímpico Universitario on 12 October.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The cauldron was for the first time lit by a female athlete, Mexican hurdler Enriqueta Basilio.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1968-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Basilio entered the Estadio Olímpico Universitario and ran a lap around the track before ascending the ramp up to the cauldron.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The **1980 Summer Olympics torch relay** was run from June 19, 1980 until July 19, 1980 prior to the 1980 Summer Olympics in Moscow.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay] The route covered around 5,000 kilometres (3,100 mi) and involved over 5,435 torchbearers.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay/1980-summer-olympics-torch-relay] Basketball player and Olympic champion Sergei Belov lit the cauldron at the opening ceremony.
